            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Miller, 53, was born in Oakland, the son of Chinese immigrants who ran a modest laundromat.  His childhood was steeped in the rhythm of the family business and the vibrant chaos of the East Bay. While his parents hoped for a more conventional path, David found solace and fascination in sketchbooks and museum visits, sparks ignited by a particularly impactful trip to the de Young Museum as a teenager.\n\nThis early artistic passion led him to pursue a Fine Arts degree at UC Berkeley, followed by a Master's at the San Francisco Art Institute. His educational journey wasn't linear; he worked part-time jobs in various cafes and restaurants across the city to fund his studies, giving him an unexpected appreciation for the intersection of art and community gathering spaces.\n\nA significant turning point came in his late 20s when he inherited a small sum from a distant relative. Instead of paying off student loans or buying property, David, against the advice of some, invested it in a struggling art gallery in North Beach. This bold move was the genesis of his career as a gallery owner and curator. The early years were challenging, filled with long hours and financial precariousness, but his keen eye for emerging artists and a dedication to fostering local talent began to pay off.\n\nDavid's personal life is intertwined with the San Francisco arts scene. He has never married but has a close-knit circle of friends \u2013 fellow artists, collectors, and creatives he's met through his work. His relationships are built on shared artistic sensibilities and mutual support. He also maintains a deep connection to his younger sister, who teaches in the public school system, a reminder of his roots.\n\nHis daily routine is a blend of the practical and the passionate. He wakes early for a walk along the Embarcadero before heading to his gallery, a short walk from his apartment in Telegraph Hill. His days are filled with curating exhibitions, meeting with artists, handling administrative tasks, and engaging with visitors. Evenings often involve gallery openings, private dinners with collectors, or simply enjoying the city's diverse culinary scene, a lingering appreciation from his student days.\n\nDavid's hopes and dreams are centered on the evolution of his gallery \u2013 expanding its reach, supporting a wider range of artists, and contributing meaningfully to San Francisco's artistic landscape. He also dreams of establishing a mentorship program for young, aspiring artists from underserved communities, a way to give back to the city that has shaped him. San Francisco is not just where he lives; it's the canvas for his life's work and the beating heart of his identity."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He remembers standing, a skinny teenager, before a Rothko at the de Young. The sheer scale and color washed over him, a sudden, profound quiet in his young mind. It felt like discovering a secret language, igniting a lifelong obsession with art's power to move the soul. This was the spark.\n\n2. The smell of burnt coffee and old paper in a North Beach cafe while sketching in his worn notebook. He felt a sense of belonging here, a shared creative undercurrent with the city itself. These quiet moments fueled his artistic drive during the lean student years, showing him art wasn't just for museums.\n\n3. Handing over that check, the bulk of his small inheritance, to the owner of the sputtering gallery. It was a leap of faith, a terrifying gamble against all logic. The anxiety twisted in his gut, but a fierce determination hardened his resolve. This was his chance to build something.\n\n4. The opening night of his first successful gallery exhibition. Seeing people connect with the art he had championed, hearing the buzz, felt like a validation of years of struggle. A surge of pride and relief washed over him; he was truly making his mark.\n\n5. Walking the Embarcadero at dawn, the city waking up around him. The cool air, the sound of the water \u2013 it grounds him. It's a moment of peaceful reflection, a reminder of the beauty and resilience of the city that has become his home and the heart of his life's passion."
